comment: no

Fantastic study can't wait to read about it.

More to the point:

I found myself thinking of Giorgia Lupi's visualization work-- not always IMMEDIATELY easy to read, but approachable once you sit down and spend some time with it.
I don't think readability inherently requires identifying individual items in the visualization.

The statements I tended to give low scores to were ones that seemed to require information about the task / context, (e.g "relevance" "key", "correctly interpret" etc.) rather than the general readability of the design as such. But this is one of the difficulties in a universal scale : sometimes questions might be asked where the reader has a clear view of the task for which it is designed, and other times they may not. Which of the questions are most useful might depend on this.

Many of the statements above use too much jargon. The statements that use jargon would not be applicable to laypeople. For example, most people don't know what "visual encoding" means. Same with trends, outliers, etc.

Frankly, they seem all relevant. It depends a bit on who you are talking to and what their background is (e.g. novices might be confused when talking about visual encodings). My ratings were all very nuanced version of "yes of course this is relevant".

So, I didn't understand what to do where I saw a negative : "I find parts of the visualization distracting" is very relevant as it's something you DON'T WANT for readability. So I listed this as relevant. It is "relevant ... for judging a study participant's perception of the readability of a visualization" ... as it hinders this. 
But this may not be what you are anticipating, and having read the instructions 3 times now I am still not sure which way to answer this one.
It I am the only person to be confused by this and all participants do the same thing ... great.
But I thought it was worth raising this now.
Sorry!
--

Also, people like "easy", "obvious" and always vote for this ... but you know what ... challenging activity is often the most rewarding and useful, learning is what humans excel at (if they can be bothered). Catching a wave is not an easy thing to do, climbing El Capitan is not an easy thing to do, reading Semiologie Graphique is not an easy thing to do (particularly if your French is ropey), learning D3 is not an easy thing to do .... but when you can do it, it's phenomenally enabling. Let's celebrate learning and challenge and what these let us achieve.
One comment: why nothing about 'attractiveness' of the visualizations?

It feels like some of these statements would be better for assessing readability among different audiences. For instance, I like the specificity of including examples in statements like "I can recognize data features (e.g., trends, minimums, outliers...) in this visualization", but I worry that visualization readers without prior training in what these words mean might not know how to answer this question.
Several of the questions seem repetitive. Also, would be helpful to have more specific details about what is easy to follow, easy to understand, etc.
Sorry, I think all of these are highly relevant for perceived readability. The reverse statements I also rated as high because if I can't interpret something, that strongly impacts the readability.

I would have thought that "I find parts of the visualization distracting" was a reversed item, as well...  
Good luck with your research!

Sometimes, some visualizations need complexity to be more effective. Like a music sheet, it's not as easy/intuitive at the beginning, but the more one learns about it, it becomes readable and quite powerful. Does this make it less readable?

I find the reversed statements seem most applicable when they are specific. I.e., "I find the visual encodings (e.g., color, shapes...) difficult to decipher in this visualization" is more relevant than "I find this visualization confusing", particularly for lay audiences. 

Some I rated as less relevant because there were other equally relevant re-phrasings (e.g., "I find data features (e.g., trends, minimums, outliers...) visible in this visualization" seems equivalent to "I can clearly see data features (e.g., trends, minimums, outliers...) in this visualization").

I struggled to settle on a clear definition of "readability" here, but my intuition is that:
1) A graphic can be readable without necessarily requiring it to surface specific kinds of data features (trends, minimums, outliers, etc.) — since some of the most readable graphics might be the simplest ones which show less detail and make these kinds of features harder to see.  
2) A graphic can be readable without supporting clear understanding and interpretation. To me these seem like additional layers. I might be able to read something very clearly but still not know what it means. 
Overall (and as is often the case when defining terms) I find it much easier to say when and why something is NOT readable that to say when it is.

"correctly" interpret the data is an odd choice for a self-report because they won't know if their interpretation is correct. I also scored items lower if I thought the wording was ambiguous or complicated.
Almost all the terms are good for the stated purpose.  It is very difficult to decide between categories 4 and 5 for most of them.

Should the following item be marked as “[reversed item]”? 
	“I find parts of the visualization distracting”
I more highly rated statements that explicitly mentioned extracting data from images. I think assessment of intuitiveness are also useful but may not relate to readability
I think the question "I find parts of the visualization distracting" is also a reversed item but you forgot to specify it.
